. After researching it the problem seems central to the Entity Framework, so the proposed solution would most likely not work. In essence, when enough entities have been touched the performance degrades catastrophically.
Our local solution is to manually chunk up the work using Autofac scopes and then recreating a new scope after an arbitrary (30) number of iterations. This indirectly leads to a new EF context being created where used. With this method the running time of the problem task has been reduced from unsustainable (>1 day) to manageable (minutes).
. We are syncing/inserting in the vicinity of 10k products using EF within the order of minutes when recreating the contexts using Autofac scopes. Have you tried profiling to detect any hot paths? We discovered some of our plugins caught every product update event and manually resolved a logger using the request lifetime scope. This alone triggered the EF degradation issue massively slowing down everything. However it sounds like you completely bypassed the service layers so unless you are manually publishing the events that might not be your problem.
