. @kfuglsang Sure.
You can use var scope = EngineContext.Current.ContainerManager.Container.BeginLifetimeScope() to fetch a new scope object. You can use this object to resolve types registered with Autofac, which will be independent from the current scope eg.
var products = scope.Resolve<IRepository<Product>>();
As a side-effect this means all services and repositories resolved using this scope will be using a fresh underlying context. Once it has gone 'stale' (performance has degraded) you can make a new one again.
Be aware that EF does not support mixing of entities from different contexts, so beware of doing this. A good rule of thumb is to use no reference types from previous scopes and to be done with all data from the current process chunk before starting on a new one with a new scope.. I originally made this service interface to reuse this pattern of "chunking"
public interface IScoped { ILifetimeScope SetScope(ILifetimeScope scope);  }
Where SetScope is meant to be implemented so it re-resolves all Autofact references in a service, eg.
```
public class SomeService : IScoped {
  private IProductService _productService;
  private ICategoryService _categoryService;
public SomeService(IProductService productService, ICategoryService categoryService) {
    _productService = productService;
    _categoryService = categoryService;
  }
public SetScope(ILifetimeScope scope) {
    _productService = scope.Resolve();
    _categoryService = scope.Resolve();
  }
}
```
I then made extension methods to facilitate chunked processing of data:
```
public static class ScopedExtensions {
private static ILifetimeScope NewScope => EngineContext.Current.ContainerManager.Container.BeginLifetimeScope();
private static ILifetimeScope RequestScope => EngineContext.Current.ContainerManager.Scope();
public static void ChunkedScopeProcessing(
    this IScoped self,
    IEnumerable input,
    int chunkSize,
    Action action
  ) {
    var scope = self.SetNewScope();
    try {
      var i = 1;
      foreach (var arg in input) {
        if (i%chunkSize == 0) {
          scope.Dispose();
          scope = self.SetNewScope();
        }
        i++;
        action(arg);
      }
    }
    finally {
      scope.Dispose();
      self.SetRequestScope();
    }
  }
public static ILifetimeScope SetRequestScope(this IScoped self) {
    return self.SetScope(RequestScope);
  }
public static ILifetimeScope SetNewScope(this IScoped self) {
    return self.SetScope(NewScope);
  }
}
```
This enables an IScoped service to call this.ChunkedScopeProcessing(input, chunkSize, action) where action is some void function, such as a void method group on this or a lambda. The result is that it runs action on the elements of the input, recreating the scope every chunkSize iterations..

